  "prompt": "If I deposit 9 lakhs by cheque into my saving account and withdraws it the same day, will the transaction come under IT notice?",
  "response": "In India, large cash transactions or suspicious banking activities can attract scrutiny from Income Tax authorities. Here are some key points to consider:\n\n1. Cash Transaction Reporting Threshold\n- Deposits or withdrawals of \u20b910 lakhs or more in a single day may trigger reporting requirements\n- Your transaction of 9 lakhs is just below this threshold\n\n2. Possible Reporting Scenarios\n- Bank may file a Suspicious Transaction Report (STR) if the transaction seems unusual\n- Income Tax Department can ask for explanation if they find the transaction suspicious\n\n3. Factors Attracting Scrutiny\n- Frequent large deposits and immediate withdrawals\n- No clear source or explanation for the transaction\n- Inconsistent transaction patterns\n\n4. Recommended Practice\n- Be prepared to explain the source and purpose of the transaction\n- Maintain proper documentation\n- Ensure transparency in financial transactions\n\n5. Official Reporting\n- Banks are required to report Cash Transaction Reports (CTR) for transactions above certain limits\n- Repeated such transactions might invite additional investigation\n\nRecommendation: If this is a one-time transaction with a legitimate purpose, you likely won't face significant issues. However, always maintain proper documentation and be prepared to explain the transaction if questioned.",
